you were getting that error because you had a return path that was not returning anything if a file was not found.  Now, when a file is found, the loop exits after assigning the file name to f.  If you do not want to return null to indicate no file, you can also raise an exception.

Other than for exceptions, it is better to have a single point of exit in the method.  Having a bunch of returns everywhere makes the code harder to understand and maintain.

You need to somehow handle the situation when the file does not exist - therefore you need to either throw exception (maybe not the best solution but also possible) or return some special &quot;marker object&quot; indicating that file was not found

I think that returning **null** is bad idea and an indicator of bad design - just think about all NPE situation you will need to remember about in the future

Better is to return *Optional* (if you have older JDK than 8, you can use Guava)

    public Optional&lt;File&gt; get_File(String fileName){
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; this.files.size(); i++) {
            if(this.files.get(i).name.equals(fileName)) {
                return Optional.of(this.files.get(i));
            }
        }
        return Optional.empty();
    }

and then just handle this when calling

    get_File(&quot;filename&quot;).orElse(...) // or even .orElseThrow(...)

The solution is as simple as follows:

    public File getFile(String fileName){
    	File file=new File(fileName);
    	int index=files.indexOf(file);
    	if(index!=-1)
    		return files.get(index);
    	return null;
    }

e.g. you can use the following program to test my solution quickly:

    import java.io.File;
    import java.util.ArrayList;
    import java.util.List;
    
    public class Demo {	
    	static List&lt;File&gt; files=new ArrayList&lt;File&gt;();
        public static void main(String[] args) {        
            files.add(new File(&quot;a&quot;));
            files.add(new File(&quot;b&quot;));
            files.add(new File(&quot;c&quot;));
            files.add(new File(&quot;d&quot;));
            System.out.println(getFile(&quot;c&quot;));
            System.out.println(getFile(&quot;x&quot;));        
        }
        public static File getFile(String fileName){
        	File file=new File(fileName);
        	int index=files.indexOf(file);
        	if(index!=-1)
        		return files.get(index);
        	return null;
        }
    }

